    culture_etiquette_md: 'Dress modestly at temples (shoulders and knees covered). Remove shoes when entering homes and temples. The royal family is deeply respected - never speak negatively about them. Pointing feet at people or Buddha images is considered rude. A gentle "wai" greeting (hands together, slight bow) is appreciated.',
    safety_women_md: 'Grab and metered taxis are widely available for getting around at any hour. In crowded areas like Chatuchak, MBK, and night markets, wearing bags cross-body is a common local habit worth adopting. Party strips like Khao San Road get loud and packed after midnight — keeping your own drinks in hand is standard practice. Temples and rural areas tend to be more conservative, so packing a light scarf or cover-up gives you flexibility across settings.',
