    getting_there_md: 'Marrakech Menara Airport (RAK) and Casablanca Mohammed V Airport (CMN) have connections from Europe and beyond. Budget airlines from European cities.',
    visa_entry_md: 'Most nationalities get 90 days visa-free on arrival. Very straightforward entry process.',
    sim_connectivity_md: 'Maroc Telecom, Orange, or Inwi offer tourist SIM cards. Available at airports and shops. Good 4G coverage in cities and tourist areas.',
    money_md: 'Moroccan Dirham (MAD). Exchange at official bureaus, not street money changers. ATMs widely available. Haggling expected in souks. Cash preferred over cards except in hotels.',
    culture_etiquette_md: 'Morocco is a Muslim country - dress modestly (shoulders and knees covered, avoid tight clothing). Remove shoes when entering homes and mosques. Use right hand for eating and greeting. Ramadan fasting should be respected. Haggling is expected and part of culture. Don\'t take photos of people without permission.',
    safety_women_md: 'Street attention and catcalling are common in cities, especially in medinas and tourist areas — a firm "la shukran" (no thank you) and walking with purpose is the standard local approach. Conservative dress (covering shoulders, knees, and avoiding tight clothing) reduces unwanted attention significantly. Many riads are women-run and offer airport pickup, local navigation tips, and guided introductions to the neighborhood. Group tours are the standard for desert trips and provide built-in logistics. Downloading offline maps of medinas before arrival makes navigation much smoother. Thousands of solo women travel Morocco each year with preparation and local knowledge.',
    transport_md: 'Good train network connecting major cities (Marrakech, Fes, Casablanca). CTM buses for longer routes. Petit taxis within cities (negotiate or insist on meter). Grand taxis between cities.',
